  "answer": "**No Old Javanese tattva text in the Falsafa corpus renders 'avidya' (Sanskrit for primordial ignorance) literally as the Sanskrit loanword *avidyā*.**[^1]\n\nInstead, the concept clusters around equivalent Kawi terms like *ajñāna* ('non-knowledge'), *lupa* ('forgetfulness'), *moha* ('delusion'), *vyāmoha* ('error'), or *andhatattva* ('principle of blindness/darkness'). These texts—Śaiva philosophical tracts on reality (*tattva*) from medieval Java—deploy *ajñāna* explicitly as the counterpart to *jñāna* (knowledge) in enumerating opposites (*viparyaya*) within *buddhi* (intellect): *dharma* vs. *adharma*, *jñāna* vs. *ajñāna*, *vairāgya* vs. *avairāgya*, *aiśvarya* vs. *anaiśvarya*.[^2] *Lupa* evokes the soul's (*ātman*) 'forgetting' its divine origin amid *māyā*'s veiling, while *moha*/*vyāmoha* denotes perceptual confusion (*bhrānta-jñāna*), as in mistaking body parts for reality due to 'blindness' (*andhatattva*).[^3]\n\nThis substitution—avoiding direct Sanskrit *avidyā* (central to Vedānta but peripheral here, where *mala*/*māyā* dominates)—signals **local exegetical authority**. These vernacular treatises (e.g., *Vṛhaspatitattva*, *Saṅ Hyaṅ Tattvajñāna*) adapt Pāñcarātra-Śaiva cosmology for Javanese audiences, prioritizing Kawi glosses (*ajñāna* as failed *pramāṇa*) over rote loans. It asserts the Javanese pandit's mastery: Sanskrit concepts are unpacked idiomatically, claiming interpretive sovereignty without deferring verbatim to Indian originals.[^4] The corpus lacks Advaita-style *avidyā*-centric discourse; ignorance is *māyā*-induced 'covering' (*āvaraṇa*) resolvable via *jñāna*-yoga, not illusion-dispelling *vidyā*.\n\n[^1]: Corpus-wide search for \"avidya\" yields zero matches in Kawi *tattva* texts; only *kṛtavidya* ('complete knower') appears once.[Slokāntara](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/#p-b503cd).\n\n[^2]: *Vṛhaspatitattva* lists *ajñāna* as *buddhi*'s perversion opposite *jñāna* (from *pratyakṣa*/*anumāna*/*āgama*); doubt (*saṅśaya*), error (*bhrānta*), etc., compound it.[Vṛhaspatitattva](/works/unknown-vrhaspatitattva-b60b28/01/transliteration/#p-9e2d55).\n\n[^3]: *Lupa* as soul's *māyā*-forgetting (*andhatattva* veils like elephant mistaking body for trunk); *moha*/*vyāmoha* as delusion.[Vṛhaspatitattva](/works/unknown-vrhaspatitattva-b60b28/01/transliteration/#p-d4e0d1); [Saṅ Hyaṅ Tattvajñāna](/works/unknown-san-hyan-tattvajnana-1f29bd/01/transliteration/#p-daaeef).\n\n[^4]: Kawi *tattva*-expositions prioritize *cetana*/*acetana* duality (*śiva* vs. *māyā*), rendering ignorance as *ajñāna*-*lupa* without *avidyā*, localizing Sanskrit *tattva*-śāstra.[Saṅ Hyaṅ Tattvajñāna](/works/unknown-san-hyan-tattvajnana-1f29bd/01/transliteration/#p-0cdcec).",
